The paper proposes a novel approach for optical flow estimation that focuses on handling occlusions and motion boundaries, which are common and difficult issues for optical flow computation. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves dense matching and variational energy minimization, which are techniques commonly used in graphics (cs.GR) and multimedia (cs.MM) research. The paper also mentions that the proposed approach is fast and robust, which suggests that it may be relevant to robotics (cs.RO) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) research.
